Run ESTIMATE on bulk and pseudobulk samples

Stephanie J. Spielman

2025-02-19

  • Setup
    • Paths
    • Read input data
  • Run ESTIMATE
  • Visualization
    • SCPCP000001
  • Export
  • Session info

The purpose of this notebook is to run ESTIMATE on bulk (counts and TPM) and pseudobulk samples and compare results to one another.

Setup

renv::load()

library(ggplot2)
library(tidyestimate)
theme_set(theme_bw())

Paths

data_dir <- here::here("analysis", "estimate", "data")
sample_metadata_file <- here::here("s3_files", "scpca-sample-metadata.tsv")
library_metadata_file <- here::here("s3_files", "scpca-library-metadata.tsv")
expression_files <- list.files(
  data_dir, 
  pattern = "_expression\\.rds$"
) |>
  purrr::set_names(
    \(x) {stringr::str_split_i(x, pattern = "_", i = 1)}
  )

output_file <- here::here("analysis", "estimate", "results", "estimate_results.tsv")

Read input data

sample_metadata_df <- readr::read_tsv(sample_metadata_file, show_col_types = FALSE)
library_metadata_df <- readr::read_tsv(library_metadata_file, show_col_types = FALSE)
expression_data <- expression_files |>
  purrr::map(
    \(filename) {
      readr::read_rds(file.path(data_dir, filename))
})

Run ESTIMATE

We will now run ESTIMATE on all three types of counts for samples in each project:

  • bulk counts
  • bulk TPM
  • pseudobulk counts
estimate_df <- expression_data |>
  # map over projects
  purrr::map(
    \(project_df_list) {
      # map over expression types
      
      purrr::map(project_df_list, \(expr_df) {
        ## Run ESTIMATE
        expr_df |> 
          dplyr::rename(hgnc_symbol = gene_symbol) |>
          tidyestimate::filter_common_genes(
            id = "hgnc_symbol", 
            tidy = TRUE, # first column contains gene symbol
            tell_missing = FALSE, 
            find_alias = TRUE
          ) |> 
          tidyestimate::estimate_score(is_affymetrix = FALSE)
      }) |> 
        purrr::list_rbind(names_to = "expression_type")
  }) |> 
  purrr::list_rbind(names_to = "project_id") |>
  dplyr::rename(sample_id = sample) |>
  # this is just the sum of scores, we won't be working with it
  dplyr::select(-estimate) |> 
  # make scores long too
  tidyr::pivot_longer(
    cols = c(stromal, immune), 
    names_to = "score_type", 
    values_to = "score"
  )

Visualization

Lets begin by looking at the overall values:

ggplot(estimate_df) + 
  aes(x = score_type, y = score, color = expression_type) + 
  geom_jitter(
    position = position_jitterdodge(jitter.height = 0, jitter.width = 0.1), 
    size = 0.75
  ) +
  scale_color_brewer(palette = "Set2") +
  facet_wrap(vars(project_id), scales = "free_x", nrow = 1) + 
  theme(legend.position = "bottom") + 
  guides(color = guide_legend(override.aes = list(size = 2)))

First, what do we see for immune scores?

  • For SCPCP000001 and SCPCP000002, pseudobulk scores tend to be higher than bulk scores
    • However, for SCPCP000001, we have a sort of trimodal distribution of values - it would be nice if this corresponded to diagnoses?!
  • For the other three projects, pseudobulk scores appear to be somewhat lower than bulk

Second, what do we see for stromal scores?

  • For SCPCP000001 and SCPCP000002, pseudobulk scores look either on par with bulk or maybe a bit lower, but that is mostly in SCPCP000001 and one outlier in SCPCP000002
  • For the other three projects, pseudobulk and bulk scores appear highly similar

The bulk distributions appear very similar to one another, so lets compare them directly next:

expr_wide_df <- estimate_df |>
  tidyr::pivot_wider(
    names_from = expression_type, 
    values_from = score
  )

ggplot(expr_wide_df) + 
  aes(x = bulk_counts, y = bulk_tpm) + 
  geom_point() +
  geom_abline(color = "darkorange2") +
  coord_equal() +
  facet_grid(
    rows = vars(score_type), 
    cols = vars(project_id)
  )

Bulk counts do not take gene length into account, but TPM does. Across all projects, we see that immune scores tend to be slightly higher for TPM, and by contrast stromal scores tend to be slightly lower for TPM compared to bulk. The effect sizes are fairly small, but the effects seem likely to be significant, which well check separately for stromal and immune. Below, we fit regressions that fix the slope to 1, so the intercept will tell us the bias from y=x:

stromal_df <- expr_wide_df |>
  dplyr::filter(score_type == "stromal")
summary(lm(bulk_tpm ~ 1 + offset(bulk_counts), data = stromal_df))

Indeed, effect sizes are not very large in the scheme of the full range of values, but they are highly significant: Compared to bulk counts, immune scores are relatively higher when calculated with TPM, and stromal scores are relatively lower whem calculated with TPM.

Lets directly compare bulk to and pseudobulk. Since TPM and bulk counts were very similar, well just visualize with the bulk counts (not TPM) here:

compare_modalities_df <- estimate_df |>
  tidyr::pivot_wider(
    names_from = expression_type, 
    values_from = score
  ) 

ggplot(compare_modalities_df) + 
  aes(x = bulk_counts, y = pseudobulk) + 
  geom_point() +
  geom_abline(color = "darkorange2") +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") +
  facet_grid(
    rows = vars(score_type), 
    cols = vars(project_id)
  ) +
  labs(title ="pseudobulk ~ bulk counts") +
  theme(aspect.ratio = 1)
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

  • There does not appear to be a significant relationship between modalities for SCPCP000002 and SCPCP000006, for either score
  • For SCPCP000001, immune scores tend to be higher in pseudobulk but stromal scores are about the same between modalities
  • For SCPCP000006 and SCPCP0000017, immune scores tend to be lower in pseudobulk but stromal scores are about the same between modalities
  • Note that projects SCPCP000001 and SCPCP000002 are single-cell, but the other three projects are single-nucleus

SCPCP000001

In SCPCP000001, we seem to have have a trimodal distribution of pseudobulk immune scores. Does any metadata variable separate these points?

library_project1 <- library_metadata_df |> 
  dplyr::filter(
    scpca_project_id == "SCPCP000001", 
    seq_unit == "bulk"
  ) |> 
  dplyr::select(scpca_sample_id, technology, library_method)

project1_df <- sample_metadata_df |>
  dplyr::filter(scpca_project_id == "SCPCP000001") |>
  dplyr::inner_join(library_project1) |>
  dplyr::inner_join(compare_modalities_df, by = c("scpca_sample_id" = "sample_id")) |>
  dplyr::filter(score_type == "immune")
Joining with `by = join_by(scpca_sample_id)`

Well first look at diagnosis:

ggplot(project1_df) + 
  aes(x = diagnosis, y = pseudobulk, color = subdiagnosis) + 
  geom_jitter(width = 0.1) + 
  ggtitle("pseudobulk ~ diagnosis") + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 30, hjust = 1))

The sample size here is too small to really draw a conclusion, but its possible that the epithelioid smples are coming out with the highest immune scores.

Lets look at a few other variables:

Doesnt look like there is much of a relationship here. Either way, what are the negative-value samples?

project1_df |>
  dplyr::filter(pseudobulk < 0, score_type == "immune")

readr::write_tsv(estimate_df, output_file)
